Part a)

The first stage data measures the response rate of VBG therapy among a fixed group of patients (n=39)(n=39). As such, I believe an appropriate model for these data is a binomial model, specifically YBin(39,)YBin(39,); well take to capture the response rate, and in the Bayesian framework is randomly distributed. Its likelihood is proportional to n(1)39nn(1)39n with nn denoting the number of successful responses, in this case 1919.

Problem 2 [Plane Crashes, 1976 - 1985]:

Part a)

If we are given that the fatal accidents in a year is distributed under Pois()Pois() then an intuitive first choice for a prior distribution is some sort of Gamma, i.e., Gam(,)Gam(,).

Jeffreys prior

I dont want to do any inferential gymnastics to guess a rate a priori (or perhaps I am just lazy) so Jeffreys prior seems like a good place to start. As we have derived in class, the Jeffreys prior for a Poisson model is lim0Gam(0.5,)lim0Gam(0.5,) and as such the posterior distribution |yGam(+yi,+n);yi=238,n=10|yGam(238.5,10).|yGam(+yi,+n);yi=238,n=10|yGam(238.5,10).

Lucky for us, the Poisson-Gamma conjugate models predictive posterior distribution exists in closed form as z|yNB(238.5,10).z|yNB(238.5,10). We can use the posterior predictive distribution and qnbinom()qnbinom() to calculate the 95% predictive interval:

qnbinom(c(0.025, 0.975), size = 238.5, mu = 23.85, lower.tail = TRUE)
## [1] 14 34

If we did not have the posterior predictive distribution in closed form, we could simulate a large number of s from the posterior distribution and draw an equally large amount of Poisson variables with our posterior parameters, then compute quantiles via MC estimates:

lambda_post_q2.1 <- rgamma(1e5, 238.5, 10)
pp_samples_q2.1 <- rpois(1e5, lambda_post_q2.1)
quantile(pp_samples_q2.1, c(0.025, 0.975))
##  2.5% 97.5% 
##    14    34

There is a 95% chance that the number of worldwide fatal accidents in 1986 is within the interval [14,34][14,34] (with a posterior expected number of fatal accidents of 23.8523.85).

Part b)

In this problem we have 1010 data points y1,,y10y1,,y10 each following an independent Poisson distribution yiPois(xi),i[1,10]yiPois(xi),i[1,10] with being the rate of fatal accidents (a random variable constant throughout distributions) and xixi being an explanatory variable proportional to the number of passenger miles flown in the year 1975+i1975+i.

Because the data does not include it we should estimate the number of passenger miles flown for each year in the dataset. Lets impute some data:

## Input data of question 2
fatalities <- data.frame(
  "Year" = 1976:1985, 
  "Accidents" = c(24, 25, 31, 31, 22, 21, 26, 20, 16, 22),
  "Deaths" = c(734, 516, 754, 877, 814, 362, 764, 809, 223, 1066),
  "Death.Rate" = c(0.19, 0.12, 0.15, 0.16, 0.14, 0.06, 0.13, 0.13, 0.03, 0.15)
  )

## Estimate the miles flown that year; ~= deaths * 1e8 / death rate
miles <- fatalities$`Deaths` * 1e8 / fatalities$`Death.Rate`
fatalities$`Miles` <- miles / 1e12

Jeffreys prior

We repeat the analysis in 2a) and get |yGam(238.5,10)|yGam(238.5,10). This time, however, we need to scale the posterior draws of by the .8.8 trillion miles flown in 19861986.

lambda_post_q2.2 <- rgamma(1e5, 238.5, 10)
pp_samples_q2.2 <- rpois(1e5, .8 * lambda_post_q2.2)
quantile(pp_samples_q2.2, c(0.025, 0.975))
##  2.5% 97.5% 
##    11    29
mean(pp_samples_q2.2)
## [1] 19.0943

There is a 95% chance that the number of worldwide fatal accidents in 1986 is within the interval [11,28][11,28] with Monte-Carlo mean 1919.

Part c)

I would suggest that it is more reasonable to assume that each year follows its own Poisson distribution, because the assumption that the fatal accidents are distributed i.i.d from a common distribution does not seem fair to me.

We can intuitively reason this by extrapolating these results into the future. As I write this in the year 2021, it does not seem fair that airplane fatalities every year come from a common distribution. If any given year records fewer than 1414 fatalities or more than 3434, then the number of fatalities lies outside the 95% CI, and having more than 3434 crashes can be reasonable the more people fly in airplanes.

We can also verify this with results. Lets simulate new observations for the year 1985, where 0.71100.7110 trillion miles were flown.

lambda_post_1985_q2 <- rgamma(1e5, 238.5, 10)
pp_samples_1985_q2.1 <- rpois(1e5, lambda_post_1985_q2)
pp_samples_1985_q2.2 <- rpois(1e5, 0.7110* lambda_post_1985_q2)

## Method 1 with one common distribution
quantile(pp_samples_1985_q2.1, c(0.025, 0.975))
##  2.5% 97.5% 
##    14    34
mean(pp_samples_1985_q2.1)
## [1] 23.85521
## Method 2 with 10 individual distributions
quantile(pp_samples_1985_q2.2, c(0.025, 0.975))
##  2.5% 97.5% 
##     9    26
mean(pp_samples_1985_q2.2)
## [1] 16.95573

Method 1 will suggest the same CI no matter what the data on miles flown. Even if a direct scaling is not accurate (as above) Method 2 with the n=10n=10 individual distributions can capture the truth of 1985 much better with the proper scale on the explanatory variable.

Also, in terms of loose sensitivity analysis, changing prior specifications for can wildly change inference for Method 1, but in Method 2 changes in prior specification can be observed the explanatory variable.

Part b)

solve_bf_q3.2 <- function(hyperparam) {
  numerator <- pbeta(0.5, hyperparam + 49, hyperparam + 69)
  return(numerator / (1 - numerator))
}
plot_q3.2 <- function(hyperparams) {
  yvals <- sapply(hyperparams, solve_bf_q3.2)
  plot(hyperparams, yvals, main = "alpha, lambda against Bayes Factor", xlab = "alpha = lambda", ylab = "BF")
  lines(hyperparams, yvals)
}

max_q3.2 <- 10000
plot_q3.2(seq(1, max_q3.2, by = 1))

solve_bf_q3.2(1e15)
## [1] 1.000001

If we let the hyperparameter specification get large enough, i.e. a very opinionated hyperparamater, the likelihood is washed out and we converge onto the BF of 11 As priors become more opinionated, we are less convinced that M1M1 represents the truth any more than M2M2 does.

Part c)

Lets try this same analysis for all prior variances [0.16,1.6,16,160,1.6103][0.16,1.6,16,160,1.6103].

question5_sa <- function(data_sums = c(320, 624), data_length = c(8, 24), data_var = c(14, 14), prior_mean = c(40, 26), var) {
  ### The only explicit parameter is prior_var, which is the prior variance according
  ### to the sensitivity analysis; both school districts will have equal prior variance
  ### The output is a dataframe summarizing posterior mean, 95% credible interval, as
  ### well as analysis on the posterior difference
  
  dataf <- data.frame("School" = c(1,2))
  
  ##Calculate posterior variances
  pos_var <- 1 / ((1 / var) + (data_length / data_var))
  dataf$`Posterior.Variance` <- pos_var
    
  ##Calculate posterior means
  pos_mean <- pos_var * ((prior_mean/var) + (data_sums/data_var))
  dataf$`Posterior.Mean` <- pos_mean  
  
  ##Calcualte 95% credible interval
  pos_lb <- qnorm(0.025, pos_mean, sqrt(pos_var))
  dataf$`95%CI.LB` <- pos_lb
  
  pos_ub <- qnorm(0.975, pos_mean, sqrt(pos_var))
  dataf$`95%CI.uB` <- pos_ub
  
  ##Calculate the 95% credible interval of the difference
  pos_diff_lb <- qnorm(0.025, pos_mean[1] - pos_mean[2], sum(sqrt(pos_var)))
  pos_diff_ub <- qnorm(0.975, pos_mean[1] - pos_mean[2], sum(sqrt(pos_var)))
  dataf$`95%CI.diff.lB` <- pos_diff_lb
  dataf$`95%CI.diff.uB` <- pos_diff_ub
  
  return((dataf))
}

for(i in c(0.16, 1.6, 16, 160, 1.6e3)){
  cat("Prior Variance:", i, "\n")
  print(knitr::kable(question5_sa(var = i)))
  cat("\n")
}

The lower our prior variance the tighter all credible intervals tend to be and the lower the posterior variance. This aligns with the fact the the diffuse prior 20=1610302=16103 gives the widest estimate for all credible intervals, reflecting a lack of information, and that small prior variances reflect opinionated beliefs which would lead to tighter CI bounds. However, on a log scale, posterior variance grows at a decreasing rate and probably converges once the prior variance becomes large enough.
